  "prompt": "Why is Modi not attending the Parliament after demonetization?",
  "response": "After the demonetization policy was announced on November 8, 2016, there were several instances where Prime Minister Narendra Modi did not attend parliamentary sessions. There could be several reasons for this:\n\n1. **Busy Schedule**: As the Prime Minister, Modi has a hectic schedule with numerous domestic and international commitments. He might have been occupied with other pressing matters of state that required his immediate attention.\n\n2. **Political Strategy**: Some political analysts suggest that Modi might have chosen to stay away from Parliament to avoid direct confrontations with the opposition, who were fiercely criticizing the demonetization move. By not attending, he could have been trying to let his ministers handle the political heat.\n\n3. **Public Outreach**: Instead of addressing Parliament, Modi chose to communicate directly with the public through various rallies and media appearances. This allowed him to maintain control over the narrative surrounding demonetization and to project a strong leadership image.\n\n4. **Delegation of Responsibilities**: Modi might have felt that the issue was being adequately handled by his cabinet ministers and other BJP leaders in Parliament, thus not necessitating his personal presence.\n\nIt's important to consider that these are speculative reasons based on the information available at the time. The specific reasons for Modi's absence would be known only to him and his close advisors.",
